    <section class="methodology-section card">
      <h2>Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>Our analysis for the best long term stocks to buy for 2025 evaluates companies across several critical dimensions to ensure a comprehensive assessment:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Financial Health:</strong> We look for robust balance sheets, manageable debt-to-equity ratios, and strong cash flow generation capabilities.</li>
        <li><strong>Growth Trajectory:</strong> Historical and projected revenue and earnings growth are heavily weighted, prioritizing sustainable expansion over short-term spikes.</li>
        <li><strong>Valuation Metrics:</strong> P/E ratios, Price-to-Sales, and PEG ratios are compared against sector averages and historical norms to identify attractive entry points.</li>
        <li><strong>Competitive Moat:</strong> Companies with distinct competitive advantages, such as technological leadership, network effects, or strong brand equity, score higher.</li>
        <li><strong>Macroeconomic Resilience:</strong> The ability to perform well across different interest rate environments and economic cycles is considered crucial for long-term viability.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What makes a stock good for the long term?</summary>
        <p>Long-term stocks typically possess a wide economic moat, a strong balance sheet, a history of consistent free cash flow generation, and management teams focused on prudent capital allocation and returning value to shareholders.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long should I hold a long-term stock?</summary>
        <p>In investing, 'long term' generally refers to a minimum holding period of 5 to 10 years, though many of the best compounders are held for decades to fully benefit from the power of compound interest.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Should I buy dividend stocks for the long term?</summary>
        <p>Dividend-paying stocks are excellent for the long term because reinvesting those dividends accounts for a massive portion of total historical stock market returns over multi-decade periods.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How often should I check my long-term stocks?</summary>
        <p>Infrequently. Monitoring them quarterly during earnings reports is sufficient. Checking daily price fluctuations often leads to emotional decision-making that harms long-term returns.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the biggest risk to a long-term buy-and-hold strategy?</summary>
        <p>The biggest risk is a fundamental deterioration in the underlying business (e.g., losing a competitive advantage or technological obsolescence) that goes unnoticed, leading an investor to hold a declining asset.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
